<div id="review_2148198998" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2148198998" />
    <a title="Anthea Cheng" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/71886340-anthea-cheng"><img alt="Anthea Cheng" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2148198998?book_show_action=true">Oct 15, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anthea Cheng" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anthea Cheng" href="/user/show/71886340-anthea-cheng">Anthea Cheng</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2148198998&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2148198998" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2495938603955125675">Crispin and his mother are serfs in 14th century England. After his mom dies, Crispin is accused of theft and murder. He is said to be a &quot;wolf’s head&quot; which means that anyone can kill him on the spot. Crispin then escapes his town to stay alive. After escaping, he comes across an abandoned town. In the town, Crispin meets a juggler known as Bear. Bear teaches Crispin to juggle, sing, play the recorder, and to have fun. They travel together and perform. But Crispin finds out that his pursuers are</span>
  <span id="freeText2495938603955125675" style="display:none">Crispin and his mother are serfs in 14th century England. After his mom dies, Crispin is accused of theft and murder. He is said to be a "wolf’s head" which means that anyone can kill him on the spot. Crispin then escapes his town to stay alive. After escaping, he comes across an abandoned town. In the town, Crispin meets a juggler known as Bear. Bear teaches Crispin to juggle, sing, play the recorder, and to have fun. They travel together and perform. But Crispin finds out that his pursuers are still looking for him. Finally, Crispin finds out that he is in fact royalty and is heir to the throne. His pursuers don't like that which is why they want to kill him. In the end, his pursuers die and Crispin and Bear are free. <br />I agree with the the main principle of "identity" in this book. Crispin spends a lot of time in this book trying to figure out who he is: a nobody, a performer, a prince, a coward, someone brave, etc. Knowing who you are and your purpose in life is a very important principle. Maybe the author could've also considered adding in more background about Bear. <br />I enjoyed this book. Crispin's struggles and adventures appealed to me in an emotional way. I haven't read much in this genre before and thought it was very interesting. I liked the theme of identity and the plot was interesting.<br />I would recommend this book to a lot of people, both peers and adults. It wouldn’t a very challenging read, so if you’re looking for a higher reading level book this wouldn’t be a good choice. This book would appeal to people who like history and realistic fiction. The plot isn’t exactly an exciting thriller, but the plot is adventurous, and there’s not much blood or anything like that. (The end has some blood when the pursuers die, but nothing serious) Overall, it was a good book and a fun read. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2495938603955125675" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

