  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2903137528?book_show_action=true">Jul 21, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emmy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emmy" href="/user/show/6688540-emmy">Emmy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6688540-emmy?shelf=kid-stuff">kid-stuff</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6688540-emmy?shelf=newbery">newbery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2903137528" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9791994311243509004">I was about 12 when this book first came out (aka, the target audience for Crispin), but I didn&apos;t read it for two reasons: 1.) I thought that the name Crispin was stupid (I don&apos;t think that now), and 2.) I didn&apos;t like the cover (I still don&apos;t).<br/><br/>This is another example of &quot;Why did this one win a Newbery award again?&quot; Because from the very beginning, I was not sure where the story was actually going. The book starts to pick up about two thirds of the way in, but for the most part, the story goes so</span>
  <span id="freeText9791994311243509004" style="display:none">I was about 12 when this book first came out (aka, the target audience for Crispin), but I didn't read it for two reasons: 1.) I thought that the name Crispin was stupid (I don't think that now), and 2.) I didn't like the cover (I still don't).<br /><br />This is another example of "Why did this one win a Newbery award again?" Because from the very beginning, I was not sure where the story was actually going. The book starts to pick up about two thirds of the way in, but for the most part, the story goes something like this:<br /><br /><i>CRISPIN: Woe is me! I am but a humble peasant, and my mother has just died. I have shown no signs of grief so far.<br /><br />PRIEST: Crispin, let us go and pray for your mother's soul.<br /><br />CRISPIN: No. I've decided to be sad now, and I'll show this sadness by running recklessly into the woods at night, where I will fall, hit my head, and awaken in time to witness something that I should not have seen. Which of course, will get me into trouble, and I will be confused about this. Why are these people upset that I witnessed their secret meeting? I don't understand!<br /><br />[skip ahead a bit, Crispin has been declared a "wolf's head" and now everyone wants to kill him]<br /><br />CRISPIN: I'm being hunted like a dog, but all I talk about is food. And I do this in the most pathetic way possible. Oh! If only someone would spare a tiny morsel, just a crust of bread--<br /><br />What is this? There is a man in that abandoned building!<br /><br />MAN: Aha! You're a fugitive, and I'm going to catch you and make you my slave!<br /><br />CRISPIN: I don't want to be your slave! (This is the first time I've shown any real emotion for the entire book!)<br /><br />MAN: That's too bad. You have no choice.<br /><br />CRISPIN: OK. I guess I'm your slave now. And any time you ask for my opinion on ANYTHING, I'll just reply that I'm your servant and have no right to any such opinion, even though it's clear that you're trying to be kind to me.<br /><br />For the rest of the book, I'm going to have zero character development. I'm about as flat and dull as a sheet of computer paper, and honestly, you'll get very little enjoyment out of this book if you're reading it just for me. But, the story is fairly interesting, so that might be a bit better. Maybe.</i><br /><br />Yeah, that's Crispin. The shorter version of the review is that Crispin has no character development (or really any character at all), so if you're reading this, read it for the plot, and not for the characters, because you're going to be somewhat disappointed. I probably would have stopped about 50-100 pages in, but since this is part of my Newbery Challenge, I plugged along. It got better, but not much.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9791994311243509004" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


